      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0911">
               <p>A native of <placeName>Salisbury</placeName>, Hall became a pupil of
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> at Lincoln
                  College on <date when="1731-01-26">Jan. 26, 1731</date>. Within a year he was
                  closely involved with the &apos;Oxford Methodists&apos;. An apparent model of
                  Christian piety, <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
                  gladly introduced Hall to his family; only to find him courting <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2182.xml"/>Martha</persName> and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2181.xml"/>Kezia</persName> at the same time in <date
                     from="1734" to="1735">1734–35</date>. Hall married <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2182.xml"/>Martha</persName> on <date when="1735-09-13"
                     >Sept. 13, 1735</date>, days after being ordained both deacon and priest,
                  professedly in order to accompany <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"
                     />CW</persName> to <placeName>Georgia</placeName>. Within a month Hall withdrew
                  from this venture. As the Methodist revival emerged, Hall was initially supportive
                  but then drawn toward the Moravian side, eventually setting up his own society. By
                  the mid-<date>1740s</date> he also proved unfaithful to <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2182.xml"/>Martha</persName>, justifying his actions by
                  appeals to polygamy in Scripture. While <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2182.xml"/>Martha</persName> stayed with her husband
                  much longer than her family could understand, this eventually fractured their
                  marriage. Hall kept up some correspondence with <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2182.xml"/>Martha</persName> until his death. See <hi
                     rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 507–8; Maser, <hi rend="italic">Sisters</hi>, 86–96;
                     <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; Tyerman, <hi rend="italic">Oxford Methodists</hi>,
                  386–411; Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 147; and <hi rend="italic"
                     >WHS</hi> 5 (<date when="1906">1906</date>): 146–51.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
